First off, a big thanks to the 38 people who participated in this survey.

This has led to some immensely helpful insights for me and department heads.

Multi-Response Questions

I've attached a PDF of graphs for the multi-response questions.

*Quick takeaways from the multi-response questions:*

   - 84% felt their department was efficient
   - But only 67% felt Pineapple as a company was efficient
   - 90% felt their department communicated well within itself and to other
   teams
   - But only 56% felt other teams communicated well to their team

So it seems that within a team things have strong ratings.

But company wide people feel differently.


Free-Answer Questions:

We got tons of great feedback here and I read every single answer
personally.

I'll be boiling these down into action steps to make sure they lead to real
meaningful changes within the organization, as well as sending out specific
feedback and ideas to managers.

*Here's a quick summary of some of the major concerns I found along with
proposed solutions:*

   - Better project briefs so all info is provided upfront, things get done
   right first time
      - Solution: standardized project request forms* (SOP)*
   - Stronger guidelines to allow people to do deep work and avoid
   distraction
      - Solution: creating deep work guidelines* (SOP)*
      - Possibly: Slack Free Fridays
   - Daily and weekly meetings in all departments to allow team to solve
   problems, clarify company and department goals and priorities
      - Solution: create guidelines for daily/weekly meetings *(SOP)*
      - Kickoff / coaching call for managers to start weekly/daily meetings
      *(event)*
      - Possibly: system for reporting about meetings to ensure they happen
   - Clearer company goals and priorities
      - Solution: Monthly CEO newsletter restating goals. *(SOP)*
      - Goals laid out in Quarterly presentations *(SOP)*
      - Goals restated in a post-presentation summary email *(SOP)*
      - Company goals restated weekly by management in weekly meetings
      * (SOP)*
   - Better understanding of how the business works
      - Create "How the business works" presentation by Brett and other
      employees explaining the basics everyone needs to know: *Who our
      customers are, how our sales pages and ads work, how our funnels
work, how
      we make money, how basic marketing and copywriting works, what split
      testing is, what common terminology/acronyms/lingo are, what are
brands and
      products and spokespeople are, etc.*
   - Lack of clarity around company's products
      - Solution: Document of all products with descriptions and photos
      *(Doc)*
      - Link to related avatar (AKA customer demo/psychographics and story)
      - Link to related sales scripts, sales pages and/or sales videos
   - Lack of clarity around people in organization, who to ask for help
      - Solution: Create interactive org charge in company intranet, with
      names and titles that click through to employee role/responsibility docs
      *(Doc)*
      - Put all role/responsibility documents in a single folder that
      everyone has access to *(Doc)*
      - Update employee role/responsibility docs *(recurring annual event)*
      - "What to ask me about" document from department heads *(Doc)*
   - Asking multiple times for answers to a question
   - Solution: Not sure
   - "Resistance" from other departments to a request
   - Dispute resolution guidelines* (SOP)*

* Note: things labeled "(SOP)" or "(Doc)" can be solved with new
documentation

*Lastly, I'll add here, there were about 50-60 employees and contractors
who chose not to share their voice...*

While I respect everyone's decisions, the feedback given here is going to
lead to real change!

If you want your voice heard, please respond to future surveys.

I read every single response everyone sent.

If something is bothering you, frustrating you, making your job less
enjoyable that you think can be fixed with some constructive feedback,
please share in the future.

If you have ideas of ways we can make the company better, please don't keep
silent. I want to hear what you're thinking.

This won't be the last time I ask for feedback and if anything, I think
we'll just ask more often now.

Thank You!

